<h3>Carboxylic Acids & Esters</h3>

<h5> A LEVEL </h5> @* Help users distinguish between Year 12 and Year 13 topics*@


<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Carboxylic acids and esters are important functional groups in organic chemistry. Carboxylic acids contain the carboxyl group (-COOH), while esters are derived from carboxylic acids and alcohols.
</p>

<h2 style="color: purple; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Carboxylic Acids</h2>

<h3 style="color: purple; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">General Formula</h3>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    The general formula for carboxylic acids is <b>RCOOH</b>, where R is an alkyl or aryl group.
</p>

<h3 style="color: purple; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Physical Properties</h3>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Boiling Points:</b> Carboxylic acids have high boiling points due to hydrogen bonding between molecules.</li>
    <li><b>Solubility:</b> Lower carboxylic acids are highly soluble in water because of hydrogen bonding. Solubility decreases as the chain length increases.</li>
    <li><b>Odor:</b> Short-chain carboxylic acids have a sharp, unpleasant smell.</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="color: purple; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Reactions of Carboxylic Acids</h3>
<ol style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Neutralization:</b> React with bases to form carboxylate salts and water. Example:
        <code>CH<sub>3</sub>COOH + NaOH → CH<sub>3</sub>COONa + H<sub>2</sub>O</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Reaction with Carbonates:</b> React with carbonates or hydrogen carbonates to form carbon dioxide, water, and a salt. Example:
        <code>2CH<sub>3</sub>COOH + Na<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub> → 2CH<sub>3</sub>COONa + CO<sub>2</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Esterification:</b> React with alcohols in the presence of an acid catalyst to form esters and water. Example:
        <code>CH<sub>3</sub>COOH + CH<sub>3</sub>OH → CH<sub>3</sub>COOCH<sub>3</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O</code>.
    </li>
</ol>

<h2 style="color: purple; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Esters</h2>

<h3 style="color: purple; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">General Formula</h3>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    The general formula for esters is <b>RCOOR'</b>, where R is the part from the carboxylic acid, and R' comes from the alcohol.
</p>

<h3 style="color: purple; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Physical Properties</h3>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Boiling Points:</b> Esters have lower boiling points than carboxylic acids due to the absence of hydrogen bonding.</li>
    <li><b>Solubility:</b> Small esters are somewhat soluble in water due to their polar nature, but solubility decreases with chain length.</li>
    <li><b>Odor:</b> Many esters have pleasant, fruity smells and are used in flavorings and perfumes.</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="color: purple; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Reactions of Esters</h3>
<ol style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Hydrolysis:</b> Esters can be hydrolyzed under acidic or basic conditions:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <b>Acid Hydrolysis:</b> Forms a carboxylic acid and an alcohol. Example:
                <code>CH<sub>3</sub>COOCH<sub>3</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O → CH<sub>3</sub>COOH + CH<sub>3</sub>OH</code>.
            </li>
            <li>
                <b>Base Hydrolysis (Saponification):</b> Forms a carboxylate salt and an alcohol. Example:
                <code>CH<sub>3</sub>COOCH<sub>3</sub> + NaOH → CH<sub>3</sub>COONa + CH<sub>3</sub>OH</code>.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ol>

